# =============================================================================
# vks-airgap-cicd — committed source of truth for every operator-tunable value.
#
# HOW TO USE
#   cp .env.example .env      # then edit .env with your air-gap specifics
#   .env is gitignored (per-operator overrides + secrets); this file is not.
#   Both the Makefile (-include .env) and scripts (they source these) read it.
#
# CONVENTIONS
#   - Non-secret values carry a real default here.
#   - `# how:` lines are ACQUISITION COMMANDS. Each is one of:
#       (verified)  we have RUN it, or it comes straight from this repo's own code/targets
#       (inferred)  from Broadcom docs whose 9.1 URLs redirect to the 9.0 tree — plausible for 9.1,
#                   NOT proven. Re-check on a real lab.
#     A command we can neither run nor cite is NOT written: the slot says UNVERIFIED and states what
#     IS established (see ARGOCD_KUBECONFIG). A wrong command gets copy-pasted; a missing one gets asked about.
#   - Secrets are COMMENTED placeholders (`<SET-IN-.env>`): set them only in .env
#     so they are never committed and never appear in `git`/`docker inspect`.
#   - Keep this file shell-clean: KEY=value, no spaces around '=', no quotes
#     needed unless the value has spaces. Escape a literal '$' as '$$' for Make.
# =============================================================================

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# 0. Run behavior
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# NOTE: the mirror mode (dual-homed vs sneakernet) is NOT a variable — it's simply WHICH mirror
# commands you run (see README "Two operating modes"): dual-homed → `make mirror`; sneakernet →
# `make mirror-pull && make bundle` (carry the bundle in) then `make bundle-load && make mirror-push`.

# Completion notifications (the terminal bell + best-effort desktop notify that long targets
# like `make mirror` / `make e2e-kind` emit when they finish). Default true. Set false to
# silence them: `make e2e-kind NOTIFY=false`, or uncomment `NOTIFY=false` here / in .env.
# COMMENTED on purpose (runtime toggle): an uncommented value would be re-sourced by load_env
# and clobber a `make … NOTIFY=false` override. Unset ⇒ the code default (true) applies.
# The bell is tty-gated and desktop-notify needs a display, so both are already no-ops in CI.
# NOTIFY=true

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# 1. Harbor (registry) — real lab: installed as a VCF Supervisor Service (Part A),
#    then DISCOVERED; KinD: auto-installed + auto-written to .env.kind.
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# stage: discover (after Part A Harbor install)  [auto in KinD (.env.kind)]
# how: after Harbor install, kubectl get svc -n <harbor-namespace> -o jsonpath='{.status.loadBalancer.ingress[0].ip}' (or the FQDN you set)
HARBOR_URL=harbor.vks.local
# Project for mirrored CI/CD + build-base infra images (Tekton, Gitea, Kaniko, temurin...)
HARBOR_INFRA_PROJECT=cicd
# Project for the built application image
HARBOR_APP_PROJECT=apps
# Create auto-created Harbor projects PUBLIC (so kubelet CAN pull anonymously).
# COMMENTED so `make mirror HARBOR_PUBLIC_PROJECTS=false` / a .env override survives (load_env
# would otherwise clobber it). Unset ⇒ scripts default to true. Set false for a private-project
# lab: the app-namespace image-pull Secret (harbor-pull) is created for you by `make gitops`, in
# EVERY app namespace, and every app's Deployment already references it — nothing to do by hand.
# HARBOR_PUBLIC_PROJECTS=true
# Path to the Harbor CA cert (self-signed). Used for crane/kaniko/podman trust.
HARBOR_CA_FILE=./secrets/harbor-ca.crt
# Registry transport. 0 (default) = HTTPS with a trusted self-signed CA (mimics VCF/VKS
# 9.1's self-signed Harbor); 1 = plain HTTP (KinD fast-iteration only). The KinD flow
# (06-install-harbor.sh) serves HTTPS on the Harbor LoadBalancer IP (cert SAN=IP) and
# publishes HARBOR_URL/HARBOR_CA_FILE to .env.kind; the CA is trusted sudo-free via
# SSL_CERT_FILE (crane) / --cert-dir (podman) / containerd certs.d / an in-cluster ConfigMap.
# Left COMMENTED (not `=0`) on purpose: this is a RUNTIME toggle, and load_env sources this
# file with `set -a`, so an uncommented value here would CLOBBER a `make e2e-kind
# HARBOR_INSECURE=1` override. Unset ⇒ the scripts default to 0 (secure). Flip it per-run
# (`make e2e-kind HARBOR_INSECURE=1`) or persist it by adding `HARBOR_INSECURE=1` to .env.
# HARBOR_INSECURE=0

# SKIP_DOTENV — ignore `.env` entirely (this file and .env.kind are still read).
# The KinD e2e sets it (E2E_SKIP_DOTENV ?= 1 in the Makefile) so a local run reproduces a
# FRESH box: the you-choose secrets do not exist and must be GENERATED, exactly as they are
# for a new operator or a CI runner. Without it, a local run silently reads YOUR .env and the
# fresh-box path is never exercised.
# Set it yourself only to sanity-check a script against a clean environment:
#   how: SKIP_DOTENV=1 make <target>          (or: make e2e-kind E2E_SKIP_DOTENV=0 to use your .env)
# COMMENTED on purpose — a runtime toggle (see HARBOR_INSECURE above).
# SKIP_DOTENV=0
# Robot/admin account used to push mirrored images + let the pipeline push builds.
# stage: after Part A install
# how: make harbor-robot (needs Harbor project-admin) → secrets/harbor-robot.env; or the Harbor admin password
HARBOR_USERNAME=admin
# how: `make harbor-robot` writes secrets/harbor-robot.env (needs Harbor project-admin) — copy the
#      password from there. If you do NOT hold project-admin: request the robot from your platform
#      admin (Scenario 2). If YOU installed Harbor (Scenario 1): it is the admin password you chose.
# HARBOR_PASSWORD=<SET-IN-.env>
# Name for the least-privilege CI robot account created by `make harbor-robot` (push+pull on the
# two mirror projects). The robot lands as `robot$<name>`; its secret is written to
# secrets/harbor-robot.env — copy HARBOR_USERNAME/HARBOR_PASSWORD from there into .env.
HARBOR_ROBOT_NAME=vks-cicd

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# 2. Gitea (self-hosted Git) — WE INSTALL on VKS
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
GITEA_NAMESPACE=gitea
# External URL (humans + webhook registration UI).
# GITEA_URL — DERIVED from GITEA_HOST (`http://${GITEA_HOST}`) by 40-install-gitea.sh and creds.sh.
# COMMENTED so GITEA_HOST stays the single source of truth for the hostname; an uncommented value
# here is exported by load_env and would pin a URL that silently disagrees with the ingress route.
# stage: you choose (optional — set it ONLY if the scheme/port differ from the ingress route)
# GITEA_URL=http://gitea.vks.local
# In-cluster URL used by TEKTON (clone + tag write-back) — resolves via kube-DNS to the Gitea
# Service. Tekton runs in this cluster, so this is correct for it. It is NOT correct for an ArgoCD
# that runs somewhere else — see GITEA_ARGOCD_URL below.
GITEA_INTERNAL_URL=http://gitea-http.gitea.svc:3000
#
# The Gitea URL ARGOCD'S repo-server clones from. It must be routable FROM THE CLUSTER ARGOCD RUNS
# IN. On a real lab ArgoCD is a Supervisor Service — a different cluster — so:
#   * gitea-http.gitea.svc:3000  resolves only INSIDE the guest cluster        -> unusable
#   * http://gitea.vks.local     exists only in YOUR /etc/hosts, in no DNS     -> unusable
#     (and dialling the ingress LB IP sends `Host: <ip>`, which matches no vhost -> 404, not a clone)
# So Gitea gets its OWN LoadBalancer (like Harbor and ArgoCD each already have) and this points at
# it. COMMENTED because 40-install-gitea.sh DISCOVERS it and publishes it; an uncommented value here
# would be exported by load_env and clobber the discovered one (and the in-cluster fallback).
# stage: discover (after `make install-gitea`)  [auto in KinD via .env.kind]
# how: kubectl -n $GITEA_NAMESPACE get svc gitea-http -o jsonpath='{.status.loadBalancer.ingress[0].ip}'
# GITEA_ARGOCD_URL=http://<gitea-lb-ip>:3000
#
# Discovered by 40-install-gitea.sh and published to .env.kind. Commented for the same reason.
# GITEA_LB_IP=<gitea-lb-ip>
#
# Gitea's Service type. Code default: LoadBalancer (an off-cluster ArgoCD must reach it; a
# LoadBalancer keeps its ClusterIP so Tekton is unaffected). Set to ClusterIP only if you know
# ArgoCD runs in THIS cluster and you cannot spare a LoadBalancer address. Commented: it has a code
# default and is a per-run override.
# GITEA_SERVICE_TYPE=LoadBalancer
# How long 40-install-gitea.sh waits for that LoadBalancer to get an address.
# GITEA_LB_TIMEOUT_SECONDS=180
# acquire: n/a (reserved — Gitea is served over HTTP; no code reads this today)
# GITEA_CA_FILE=./secrets/gitea-ca.crt   # reserved — Gitea is served over HTTP (no TLS); no code reads it today
GITEA_ORG=demo
# NO GITEA_APP_REPO / GITEA_DEPLOY_REPO here on purpose. With more than one app they are PER-APP
# (<app>-app / <app>-deploy, derived from apps/registry.tsv by scripts/lib/apps.sh). A global value
# would be exported by load_env's `set -a` and CLOBBER the loop's per-app export — every app would
# be seeded into javawebapp's repos. That is the .env.example clobber class (check-env-clobber).
GITEA_ADMIN_USER=gitea_admin
# stage: you choose (login for the component we install / KinD only)
# GITEA_ADMIN_PASSWORD=<SET-IN-.env>
# Persistent volume size for Gitea data (SQLite DB + repos).
GITEA_STORAGE_SIZE=5Gi
# CI user Tekton/ArgoCD use to clone + push (write-back). A PAT is minted at seed time.
GITEA_CI_USER=ci-bot
# stage: you choose (login for the component we install / KinD only)
# GITEA_CI_PASSWORD=<SET-IN-.env>
# GITEA_CI_TOKEN=<SET-IN-.env — minted by scripts/50-seed-gitea-repos.sh>

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# 3. Tekton — WE INSTALL on VKS
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
TEKTON_NAMESPACE=tekton-pipelines
# Namespace where the pipeline, triggers, and EventListener run.
CI_NAMESPACE=ci

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# 4. ArgoCD (GitOps CD) — PROVIDED by VKS
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# TOPOLOGY (real lab, confirmed against Broadcom 9.1 "Install the Argo CD Operator/Instance"):
# ArgoCD is a Supervisor Service — the operator + argocd-server run ON THE SUPERVISOR, in a vSphere
# Namespace (e.g. argocd-instance-1), NOT in the guest/workload cluster. So to deploy javawebapp INTO the guest
# cluster (VKS_CLUSTER_NAME), that cluster must be REGISTERED as an ArgoCD destination (`argocd cluster add`,
# or the argocd-attach-service CRs) and the Application's destination pointed at it. The committed Application
# (k8s/argocd/application.yaml) uses the IN-CLUSTER destination (https://kubernetes.default.svc) — correct for
# KinD (one cluster: ArgoCD's own == the workload cluster), but on a real Supervisor-hosted ArgoCD that
# resolves to the SUPERVISOR, not the guest cluster. `make argocd-preflight` reports TOPOLOGY OK / MISMATCH
# for exactly this. ARGOCD_NAMESPACE = the k8s namespace the ArgoCD instance watches Applications in
# (real lab: the vSphere Namespace the instance runs in, e.g. argocd-instance-1; KinD: argocd).
ARGOCD_NAMESPACE=argocd
# stage: discover (after Part A ArgoCD install)  [auto in KinD (.env.kind) as ARGOCD_LB_IP]
# how (verified command shape; the NAMESPACE `argocd-instance-1` is inferred from 9.0 docs — confirm on your lab):
#      kubectl get svc -n <argocd-vsphere-namespace> argocd-server -o jsonpath='{.status.loadBalancer.ingress[0].ip}'
ARGOCD_SERVER=argocd.vks.local
# Path to the ArgoCD server's self-signed CA cert. Fetch it with `make fetch-argocd-ca`
# (from ARGOCD_LB_IP in KinD, or the lab's argocd-server LoadBalancer IP). Leave unset if
# ArgoCD presents a publicly-trusted cert or you use the argocd CLI's --insecure/accept flow.
# how: make fetch-argocd-ca   (fetches the ArgoCD server's self-signed CA from its endpoint)
# ARGOCD_CA_FILE=./secrets/argocd-ca.crt
# NO ARGOCD_APP_NAME / ARGOCD_DEST_NAMESPACE here on purpose: one ArgoCD Application PER APP, each
# deploying into its OWN namespace (named after the app). Both are derived from apps/registry.tsv.
# A global value here would clobber the per-app export (see the note on the Gitea repos above).
# API server the Application deploys to. Commented ⇒ code default https://kubernetes.default.svc
# (IN-CLUSTER: KinD, or ArgoCD-in-guest). On a real lab where ArgoCD runs on the SUPERVISOR, set this
# to the GUEST cluster's API URL so ArgoCD deploys THERE, not on the Supervisor — `make argocd-register-guest`
# registers the guest cluster and sets it for you (admin path; a tenant requests registration — see §4 topology).
# Commented (not =…) so the in-cluster default applies for KinD and a real-lab value / register step isn't clobbered.
# ARGOCD_DEST_SERVER=https://kubernetes.default.svc
# The AppProject each Application belongs to. Code default: `default`, which permits every
# destination and every repo — correct for KinD and for Scenario 1 (you installed ArgoCD, so you are
# its admin). A TENANT (Scenario 2) is given their OWN AppProject, and an Application whose project
# does not permit its destination + its repo is REJECTED. So set this to your AppProject, and ask
# your platform admin to add — per app — the app's namespace to `spec.destinations` and the
# <app>-deploy repo URL to `spec.sourceRepos`. (It used to be hardcoded in the manifest AND absent
# from the envsubst allowlist, so it could not be changed even by editing the file.)
# Commented: it has a code default and is a per-run override.
# how: kubectl -n $ARGOCD_NAMESPACE get appprojects.argoproj.io
# ARGOCD_PROJECT=default
# How long `make gitops` waits for ArgoCD to actually FETCH a revision from the deploy repo before
# it fails. This is the gate that proves ArgoCD's repo-server can reach GITEA_ARGOCD_URL — a wrong
# URL used to sync green forever (an Application ArgoCD never reconciled has no error to report).
# ARGOCD_REPO_TIMEOUT_SECONDS=180
# Branch in <app>-deploy that ArgoCD tracks (must be a branch, not a tag/commit,
# so the Tekton write-back commit is picked up automatically).
ARGOCD_TRACK_BRANCH=main
# ArgoCD UI/API transport in KinD. 0 (default) = upstream self-signed TLS on 443,
# reached by the ArgoCD LoadBalancer IP with `--insecure` (mimics VCF/VKS 9.1's
# self-signed ArgoCD); 1 = server.insecure plain HTTP (KinD fast-iteration only).
# 07-install-argocd.sh exposes argocd-server on its OWN LoadBalancer (not the ingress,
# matching VKS) and publishes ARGOCD_LB_IP to .env.kind.
# Left COMMENTED (not `=0`) for the same reason as HARBOR_INSECURE above: a runtime toggle
# an uncommented value would clobber. Unset ⇒ default 0 (secure). Flip per-run
# (`make e2e-kind ARGOCD_INSECURE=1`) or persist by adding `ARGOCD_INSECURE=1` to .env.
# ARGOCD_INSECURE=0

# --- Cross-cluster ArgoCD: registering the GUEST cluster as a destination ------------------
# WHEN you need this: ArgoCD runs in a DIFFERENT cluster from where javawebapp deploys. On a real VKS
# lab that is the normal case — ArgoCD is a Supervisor Service running ON THE SUPERVISOR, while the
# app must land in the GUEST/workload cluster. The committed Application uses the in-cluster
# destination (correct for KinD, where they are the same cluster), which on a Supervisor-hosted
# ArgoCD would resolve to the SUPERVISOR. `make argocd-preflight` reports TOPOLOGY OK / MISMATCH.
#
# HOW it happens: set ARGOCD_KUBECONFIG below and run `make gitops` (or `make install-all`) —
# it AUTO-INVOKES `make argocd-register-guest` first. You never run kubectl by hand.
#
# What registration does (scripts/71-argocd-register-guest.sh, all declarative kubectl):
#   guest cluster : creates the `argocd-manager` ServiceAccount + a cluster-admin binding + a
#                   NON-EXPIRING service-account-token Secret;
#   ArgoCD cluster: writes ArgoCD's `Cluster` Secret (argocd.argoproj.io/secret-type: cluster)
#                   carrying the guest API URL + CA + that bearer token;
#   then publishes ARGOCD_DEST_SERVER so the Application targets the guest.
# It does NOT install a second ArgoCD in the guest, and it deliberately does NOT use
# `argocd cluster add`: that stores an EXPIRING credential when the source kubeconfig authenticates
# with an x509 client cert (argoproj/argo-cd#13175) — which is exactly what
# `vcf cluster kubeconfig get` hands you — so the registered cluster would later flip to Unknown.
#
# ADMIN-ONLY: minting the argocd-manager cluster-admin RBAC needs cluster-admin on the guest, and
# ArgoCD's `clusters` is a global RBAC resource. A pure VKS tenant REQUESTS this from the platform
# team; they cannot self-service it.
#
# Path to the kubeconfig of the cluster ARGOCD RUNS IN. Leave UNSET when ArgoCD and the workload
# share a cluster (KinD, and any single-cluster deploy) — registration is then skipped entirely.
#
# On a real lab ArgoCD is a Supervisor Service, so this is a kubeconfig for the SUPERVISOR (scoped to
# the vSphere Namespace the ArgoCD instance runs in, e.g. argocd-instance-1) — NOT the workload
# cluster. `vcf cluster kubeconfig get` fetches the WORKLOAD cluster's kubeconfig; that is KUBECONFIG.
#
#   how (INFERRED — Broadcom 9.0-via-redirect docs; we have never run it on a lab):
#      make fetch-argocd-kubeconfig
#   which runs, per Broadcom ("Connect to the Supervisor as a vCenter SSO User" + "VCF CLI Context,
#   Architecture, and Configuration"): a Supervisor context is created with
#   `vcf context create --endpoint https://$SUPERVISOR_HOST --username <u>@$VKS_SSO_DOMAIN ...`, the
#   VCF CLI "respects the KUBECONFIG environment variable for writing to alternate locations", so we
#   point KUBECONFIG at this file; creating a Supervisor context also auto-creates the per-vSphere-
#   Namespace contexts (`<ctx>` and `<ctx>:<namespace>`), and we select `<ctx>:$ARGOCD_NAMESPACE`.
#   The target then PROVES it works (argocd-server must be visible) rather than trusting the file.
#   It is INTERACTIVE (the CLI prompts for the password; a password on argv is forbidden).
# ARGOCD_KUBECONFIG=./secrets/argocd.kubeconfig
#
# Name of the VCF CLI context created for the Supervisor by `make fetch-argocd-kubeconfig`.
# ARGOCD_SUPERVISOR_CONTEXT=argocd-supervisor
#
# The Supervisor's CA certificate (preferred over skipping TLS verification).
#   how: ask your vSphere admin, or download it from the Supervisor endpoint.
# VKS_CA_CERT_FILE=./secrets/supervisor-ca.crt
#
# Path to the GUEST/workload cluster's kubeconfig. Defaults to the flow's $KUBECONFIG, so you
# normally do NOT set this.
#   how (INFERRED — from Broadcom 9.0-via-redirect docs; never run on a lab by us. This is the
#        WORKLOAD-cluster kubeconfig; do not confuse it with ARGOCD_KUBECONFIG, which is the
#        SUPERVISOR's and is an open question — see below):
#      vcf cluster kubeconfig get $VKS_CLUSTER_NAME --export-file ./secrets/vks.kubeconfig
# GUEST_KUBECONFIG=./secrets/vks.kubeconfig
#
# The guest API URL ArgoCD will DIAL. It must be routable FROM THE ARGOCD CLUSTER — the address in
# your kubeconfig may be reachable from your laptop but not from the Supervisor. Defaults to the
# guest kubeconfig's server. Set it when they differ (e.g. the guest control-plane VIP).
#   how: kubectl --kubeconfig $GUEST_KUBECONFIG config view --minify -o jsonpath='{.clusters[0].cluster.server}'
# GUEST_API_SERVER=https://<guest-api-vip>:6443
#
# Name the registered destination appears under in ArgoCD. Defaults to the guest context name.
# ARGOCD_DEST_CLUSTER_NAME=vks-guest
#
# The ServiceAccount minted on the guest for ArgoCD to act through (+ its namespace).
# ARGOCD_MANAGER_SA=argocd-manager
# ARGOCD_MANAGER_NS=kube-system
#
# Skip TLS verification of the GUEST API when registering. Only for a stand-in whose API cert has
# no SAN for the address ArgoCD dials (the two-KinD e2e). Never on a real lab.
# ARGOCD_REGISTER_INSECURE=0

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# 4b. Ingress (WE install it) — ONE LoadBalancer fronting the browser UIs at
#     *.vks.local so operators reach Gitea/ArgoCD/the app by hostname instead of
#     `kubectl port-forward`. Air-gap honest: hostnames resolve via /etc/hosts on
#     the jump box/clients -> the ingress LB IP (NO internet DNS / sslip.io).
#     Harbor keeps its OWN direct LoadBalancer (its LB IP is load-bearing for the
#     containerd insecure-registry pull path — see 06-install-harbor.sh).
#
#     Pluggable: INGRESS_CONTROLLER selects the implementation.
#       istio           (default) — WE install the Istio control plane + ingress gateway
#                                   (images from Harbor via the helm hub override).
#       istio-existing            — the platform team ALREADY installed Istio; we install
#                                   NOTHING and only attach our routes to their gateway.
#                                   Run `make istio-preflight` first — it discovers the mesh
#                                   and tells you exactly what (if anything) to request from
#                                   the mesh admin.
#       traefik                   — the lighter single-binary Traefik.
#     All expose the SAME *.vks.local hostnames behind one LB IP.
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
INGRESS_CONTROLLER=istio
# Ingress hostnames — the UIs the ingress fronts. GITEA_HOST is the SINGLE source of truth for
# Gitea's hostname: GITEA_URL derives from it (see §3) rather than repeating it.
#
# There is deliberately NO ARGOCD_HOST: ArgoCD is NOT routed through the ingress (neither is
# Harbor). Each keeps its OWN LoadBalancer — Harbor's LB IP is load-bearing for the containerd
# registry-pull path, and ArgoCD's own self-signed-TLS LB mirrors the VKS lab. Reach ArgoCD at
# ARGOCD_SERVER / ARGOCD_LB_IP, not at a *.vks.local name. (An ARGOCD_HOST=argocd.vks.local
# knob used to sit here with ZERO consumers in the entire repo — it promised a route that does
# not exist.)
GITEA_HOST=gitea.vks.local
# APPS_REGISTRY — the app registry the loops read (apps/registry.tsv): one row per demo app.
# COMMENTED: the code reads it as `${APPS_REGISTRY:-${REPO_ROOT}/apps/registry.tsv}` (a DYNAMIC
# fallback), and an uncommented value here would be exported by load_env's `set -a` and pin it,
# defeating the fallback. Override only to point the loops at a different registry (e.g. a test one).
# stage: you choose (optional)
# APPS_REGISTRY=./apps/registry.tsv

# APP_DOMAIN — the DNS suffix every app's ingress hostname is DERIVED from: an app in
# apps/registry.tsv is reachable at <app>.${APP_DOMAIN} (app_host(), scripts/lib/apps.sh).
# There is deliberately NO per-app <APP>_HOST variable here: that made "adding an app is ONE ROW"
# false (a new row died until you also added a line to THIS file) and no gate could see the second
# edit. One global instead — which is also what lets a shared Istio Gateway admit every app at once
# with a single `*.${APP_DOMAIN}` entry. Only the domain is operator-tunable; the <app> part IS the
# registry row.
APP_DOMAIN=vks.local
TEKTON_DASHBOARD_HOST=tekton.vks.local
# --- Istio: WE install it (INGRESS_CONTROLLER=istio) ---
# ISTIO_VERSION must match images/images.txt istio/pilot + istio/proxyv2 tags;
# Renovate bumps it in lockstep with them (Docker images group), and
# check-image-alignment is the deterministic backstop.
# renovate: datasource=docker depName=istio/pilot
ISTIO_VERSION=1.30.2
ISTIO_NAMESPACE=istio-system
#
# --- Istio: SOMEONE ELSE installed it (INGRESS_CONTROLLER=istio-existing) ---
#
# WHICH ROUTE API. Left COMMENTED = auto: prefer the Kubernetes Gateway API whenever Istio is an
# accepted GatewayClass, else fall back to the classic Gateway/VirtualService API.
#   gateway-api  what Broadcom's VKS walkthrough uses (`gatewayClassName: istio`). Needs NOTHING
#                from the mesh admin: we create a Gateway in our own namespace and Istio
#                auto-provisions the proxy AND its LoadBalancer (the proxy inherits istiod's
#                image hub, so on an air-gapped cluster it pulls from Harbor automatically).
#                This also works when the VKS Istio package's shared ingress gateway is OFF —
#                which is its DEFAULT (istio.gateways.ingress.enabled=false).
#   classic      Gateway + VirtualService bound to an EXISTING shared gateway workload. Requires
#                that gateway to exist, plus its selector label (discovered) and usually rights
#                in its namespace.
#   how: kubectl get gatewayclass istio -o jsonpath='{.status.conditions[?(@.type=="Accepted")].status}'
# ISTIO_ROUTE_API=auto
#
# Gateway-API only: the namespace holding the Gateway we create (Istio provisions
# `<ISTIO_GATEWAY_NAME>-istio` — the proxy Deployment + its LoadBalancer Service — right here).
# ISTIO_GWAPI_NAMESPACE=vks-ingress
#
# Gateway-API only: the GatewayClass to attach to. `istio` is Istio's own.
# ISTIO_GATEWAY_CLASS=istio
#
# ALL of these stay COMMENTED: they are DISCOVERED from the live cluster by
# scripts/lib/istio.sh. Setting one here would be sourced into the environment and
# would SKIP discovery for that value — pinning us to our own install's naming and
# hiding the platform team's real gateway. Uncomment one only to OVERRIDE discovery
# (e.g. you have no RBAC to read the gateway namespace and the mesh admin gave you
# the values, or the cluster has more than one ingress gateway and you must choose).
#
# Namespace of the ingress-gateway Service.
#   how: kubectl get svc -A -o json | jq -r '.items[]|select(any(.spec.ports[]?;.port==15021))|select(.spec.selector.istio!=null)|.metadata.namespace'
#   (port 15021 is the istio-proxy status-port — it identifies a GATEWAY. istiod does
#    NOT expose it, so this will not accidentally match the control plane.)
# ISTIO_GATEWAY_NAMESPACE=istio-ingress
#
# Name of that Service.
#   how: kubectl get svc -A -o json | jq -r '.items[]|select(any(.spec.ports[]?;.port==15021))|select(.spec.selector.istio!=null)|.metadata.name'
# ISTIO_GATEWAY_SERVICE=istio-ingressgateway
#
# The VALUE of the gateway's `istio:` selector label. THE load-bearing value: a Gateway
# must select the gateway workload with exactly `istio: <this>`. The istio/gateway helm
# chart derives it from the HELM RELEASE NAME, so on a mesh you did not install it is
# very unlikely to be `ingressgateway`. A Gateway with a non-matching selector is accepted
# by the API server with NO error and binds nothing -> connection refused, not a 404.
#   how: kubectl -n <ns> get svc <svc> -o jsonpath='{.spec.selector.istio}'
# ISTIO_GATEWAY_LABEL=ingressgateway
#
# Name of the Gateway resource WE create (when we are allowed to create one).
# ISTIO_GATEWAY_NAME=vks-uis
#
# Set ONLY when the platform team owns a shared Gateway that you may reference but not
# create: we then create NO Gateway and only VirtualServices (in our own namespaces).
# Its servers[].hosts must admit our three UI hosts (exactly, or via a *.vks.local
# wildcard) — `make istio-preflight` asserts this instead of letting the routes
# silently never match.
#   how: ask the mesh admin; then `kubectl -n <ns> get gateway <name> -o jsonpath='{.spec.servers[*].hosts}'`
# ISTIO_SHARED_GATEWAY=istio-ingress/shared-gw
#
# Set ONLY if the gateway is NOT a LoadBalancer (or is fronted by something else) and you were
# given the address that reaches it. Normally the address is RESOLVED from the live gateway.
#
# NOTE the distinct name: INGRESS_LB_IP itself is OUR PUBLISHED STATE (every install/attach writes
# the address it resolved into .env.kind), so it is always set after a previous run and can never
# be trusted as an input — consuming it once made a Gateway-API attach report the PREVIOUS classic
# gateway's IP while the route check passed through stale classic routes (a false green). The
# override therefore has its own variable, which nothing auto-publishes.
# INGRESS_LB_IP_OVERRIDE=10.0.0.42
# --- Traefik (INGRESS_CONTROLLER=traefik) ---
TRAEFIK_NAMESPACE=traefik

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# 4c. Pod Security Admission (PSA) — REQUIRED for a real VKS guest cluster
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# A VKS guest cluster runs the PSA controller and ENFORCES the `restricted` Pod Security
# Standard BY DEFAULT from VKS/TKr v1.26 — "pods violating security are rejected unless
# namespace configuration is changed" (Broadcom, "Configure PSA for VKr 1.25 and Later").
# Only kube-system / tkg-system / vmware-system-cloud-provider are exempt; every namespace
# WE create is not. KinD enforces nothing, so a stack that installs cleanly locally can have
# its pods REJECTED outright on a real lab — invisibly.
#
# So we label each namespace we create with the MINIMUM level its workloads actually need.
# These defaults were MEASURED against a live cluster, not guessed — re-derive them any time
# with `make psa-check` (it uses a server-side dry-run label, so the API server evaluates the
# real running pods and reports the violations; it changes nothing).
#
# Values: restricted | baseline | privileged | none (none = do not label; for a cluster whose
# platform team manages PSA centrally, e.g. via the podSecurityStandard ClusterClass variable).
#
# gitea / tekton-pipelines / javawebapp are restricted-clean as they ship.
PSA_LEVEL_GITEA=restricted
PSA_LEVEL_TEKTON=restricted
PSA_LEVEL_APP=restricted
# The CI namespace runs the build TaskRuns. KANIKO BUILDS AS ROOT (runAsUser=0, unrestricted
# capabilities, no seccompProfile), so `restricted` REJECTS them. baseline is genuinely required
# here — it is not a workaround. (A restricted-only platform would need a rootless builder.)
PSA_LEVEL_CI=baseline
# The namespace holding our Gateway. The proxy Istio AUTO-PROVISIONS there sets no
# seccompProfile, so `restricted` rejects it — and that pod is created by the platform's istiod,
# NOT by us, so we cannot make it compliant. baseline is required.
PSA_LEVEL_INGRESS=baseline
# istio-system, when WE install the mesh (Scenario 1): istiod sets no seccompProfile.
# On a real lab the platform owns this namespace and this value is unused.
PSA_LEVEL_ISTIO_SYSTEM=baseline

# --- Additional operator knobs (surfaced by `make check-env-coverage`) ---------------------
# Harbor's helm chart repository. Point these at an INTERNAL chart mirror for a fully air-gapped
# install (the chart is fetched on the internet side; the IMAGES come from Harbor either way).
HARBOR_CHART_REPO_NAME=harbor
HARBOR_CHART_REPO_URL=https://helm.goharbor.io
# Where the ArgoCD install manifest is cached between runs (avoids re-downloading it).
# COMMENTED: the code derives it as `${TMPDIR:-/tmp}/vks-airgap-cicd-manifests`
# (07-install-argocd.sh:72). Pinning /tmp here would export it and make TMPDIR ignored.
# stage: you choose (optional — a fixed cache dir)
# ARGOCD_MANIFEST_CACHE=/tmp/vks-airgap-cicd-manifests
# Namespace the Istio CONTROL PLANE runs in. COMMENTED on purpose: in istio-existing mode it is
# DISCOVERED (`kubectl get deploy -A -l app=istiod`). Uncomment ONLY to override discovery — e.g.
# you lack RBAC to list deployments cluster-wide and the mesh admin told you the namespace.
#   how (verified): kubectl get deploy -A -l app=istiod -o jsonpath='{.items[0].metadata.namespace}'
# ISTIOD_NAMESPACE=istio-system
# Sneakernet bundle output (see `make bundle` / `make bundle-load`).
#
# BUNDLE_OUT_DIR — where `make bundle` WRITES the tarball. COMMENTED on purpose, and it must stay
# that way: load_env sources this file with `set -a`, so an uncommented value is exported and
# CLOBBERS a `make bundle BUNDLE_OUT_DIR=<dir>` override. It used to say `./bundle`, which broke
# `make e2e-sneakernet` outright — that target passes a transfer dir, the clobber sent the tarball
# INTO ./bundle (the directory tar is archiving), and tar failed with "file changed as we read it".
# Unset ⇒ the code default (the repo root); 11-bundle.sh also now REFUSES to write inside BUNDLE_DIR.
# stage: you choose (optional — a per-run destination, e.g. a USB mount)
# BUNDLE_OUT_DIR=/media/usb
# BUNDLE_TARBALL — the carried tarball that `make bundle-load` unpacks on the air-gap box.
# COMMENTED, for the same reason as BUNDLE_OUT_DIR above: 20-bundle-load.sh requires it
# (`${BUNDLE_TARBALL:?}`) and every caller passes it per-run — `make bundle-load
# BUNDLE_TARBALL=/path/to/vks-airgap-cicd-bundle-*.tar.zst`, and jumpbox-run.sh does the same for
# the sneakernet e2e. An uncommented value here is exported by load_env's `set -a` and CLOBBERS
# that override, so bundle-load looked for ./bundle.tar.gz and died `bundle not found` while the
# real tarball sat in the transfer dir. There is no sensible default: the filename is timestamped.
# stage: you choose (the path of the tarball you actually carried across)
# BUNDLE_TARBALL=/media/usb/vks-airgap-cicd-bundle-20260712-184355.tar.zst
# acquire: choose (a toggle, not a value to obtain)
# `make mirror-verify` fast mode: check the manifest/digest only, skip full blob validation.
# MIRROR_VERIFY_FAST=0
# Gitea admin email (used when the admin account is created).
GITEA_ADMIN_EMAIL=admin@vks.local

# GITEA_LOCAL_PORT — the local port `make creds` / the e2e port-forward Gitea on.
# stage: you choose (optional — leave UNSET and the code picks a free ephemeral port)
# COMMENTED on purpose. The code reads it as `${GITEA_LOCAL_PORT:-$(pick_port)}`
# (50-seed-gitea-repos.sh:27, 99-verify.sh:25): unset ⇒ an EPHEMERAL port, so two runs on
# one box never collide. Because load_env sources this file with `set -a`, an UNCOMMENTED
# value here is exported and CLOBBERS that fallback — pinning 3000 for everyone and
# silently destroying the parallel-safety the code comments promise. Uncomment ONLY if you
# deliberately want a fixed port.
# GITEA_LOCAL_PORT=3000
#
# APP_LOCAL_PORT — the local port `make verify` port-forwards the app on (99-verify.sh:26).
# stage: you choose (optional — leave UNSET and the code picks a free ephemeral port)
# Same rule as GITEA_LOCAL_PORT: read as `${APP_LOCAL_PORT:-$(pick_port)}`, so leave it COMMENTED
# or you pin the port for everyone and lose parallel-run safety.
# APP_LOCAL_PORT=8080

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# 5. Demo application
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# NO APP_NAME here: it is per-app (apps/registry.tsv). APP_BRANCH and APP_REPLICAS below ARE global
# — they apply to every app equally, so a single value is correct.
# Branch of each <app>-app repo that a push triggers CI on.
APP_BRANCH=main
# Container port the app binds — consumed by the app Dockerfile (`ARG APP_INTERNAL_PORT`) and by
# local `make app-run`. It does NOT change the in-cluster port: deploy/javawebapp/deployment.yaml pins
# containerPort 8080 (and SERVER_PORT=8080), because that manifest is seeded into the javawebapp-deploy
# repo and is not rendered from this file. Changing this alone will NOT move the pod's port.
APP_INTERNAL_PORT=8080
# Host port for LOCAL dev runs (mvn spring-boot:run / java -jar). check-ports guards it.
APP_DEV_PORT=8080
# Replicas ArgoCD deploys.
APP_REPLICAS=2
# Air-gap Maven builder image tag (deps pre-baked; built by scripts/15-build-push-builder.sh).
# Its ref is derived as $HARBOR_URL/$HARBOR_INFRA_PROJECT/javawebapp-builder:$BUILDER_IMAGE_TAG.
# Rebuild + bump when apps/java/javawebapp/pom.xml dependencies change.
BUILDER_IMAGE_TAG=0.3.0

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# 6. VKS access (VCF 9 + Supervisor) — see scripts/30-vks-login.sh
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# ACQUISITION ORDER (real lab): (A) set the upfront vCenter vars — SUPERVISOR_HOST,
# VKS_NAMESPACE, VKS_CLUSTER_NAME, VKS_USERNAME; (B) get the workload kubeconfig with
# `vcf cluster kubeconfig get` (see KUBECONFIG how: below); (C/D) DISCOVER Harbor's and
# ArgoCD's LB IPs AFTER you install them in Part A (see §1/§4 how: comments); (E) you
# CHOOSE the Gitea passwords (§2) for the components WE install. KinD needs NONE of this:
# the kind steps auto-DISCOVER every value and write them to a gitignored .env.kind overlay
# (sourced last), so `make e2e-kind` runs with zero manual .env setup.
#
# Everything downstream only needs a working KUBECONFIG + context. 30-vks-login.sh
# is the single pluggable step that produces them.
# stage: generated by `vcf cluster kubeconfig get` (real lab) / auto in KinD (.env.kind)
# how (INFERRED — Broadcom 9.0-via-redirect docs; we have never run it on a lab. Auto-written by KinD.):
#      vcf cluster kubeconfig get $VKS_CLUSTER_NAME --export-file $KUBECONFIG   (after `vcf context create/use`)
#      legacy 8.x: kubectl vsphere login --tanzu-kubernetes-cluster-name $VKS_CLUSTER_NAME \
#                    --tanzu-kubernetes-cluster-namespace $VKS_NAMESPACE --server $SUPERVISOR_HOST --vsphere-username $VKS_USERNAME
KUBECONFIG=./secrets/vks.kubeconfig
# KUBECONFIG context to select after login (the context name INSIDE the kubeconfig).
# Distinct from VKS_CONTEXT_NAME below (the vcf-CLI context NAME, only for VKS_AUTH_METHOD=vcf).
VKS_CONTEXT=vks-workload
# Auth method 30-vks-login.sh uses to produce KUBECONFIG + context (code default: kubeconfig).
#   kubeconfig = use the KUBECONFIG above as-is (KinD writes this into .env.kind automatically)
#   vcf        = vcf-CLI login (real VKS lab)   |   vsphere = kubectl-vsphere plugin login
# Commented so the code default applies and a `make vks-login VKS_AUTH_METHOD=…` override is not clobbered.
# VKS_AUTH_METHOD=kubeconfig
#
# --- VCF-CLI login inputs (VKS_AUTH_METHOD=vcf; real VKS lab) ---
# The flow is INTERACTIVE (prompts for the context name + password — no password on argv):
#   vcf context create --endpoint https://$SUPERVISOR_HOST --username <user>@<SSO-DOMAIN> \
#       [--insecure-skip-tls-verify] --auth-type basic
#   vcf context use <VKS_CONTEXT_NAME>:<VKS_NAMESPACE>
# stage: set upfront (vCenter)
# where: vCenter → Workload Management → Supervisors → Control Plane IP
# SUPERVISOR_HOST=<SET-IN-.env>       # Supervisor / VCF endpoint (host or IP, no scheme)
# stage: set upfront (vCenter)
# where: the vSphere Namespace name in vCenter (the <ns> in `context use <name>:<ns>`)
# VKS_NAMESPACE=<SET-IN-.env>         # the vSphere SUPERVISOR namespace where the guest cluster is provisioned
#                                     #   and where the Supervisor Services (Harbor, ArgoCD) run — NOT a k8s
#                                     #   namespace inside the guest cluster. (The <ns> in `vcf context use <name>:<ns>`.)
# stage: set upfront (vCenter) — your vSphere SSO admin, e.g. administrator@vsphere.local
# VKS_USERNAME=<SET-IN-.env>          # 'user@SSO.DOMAIN' (e.g. administrator@WLD.SSO)
# VKS_SSO_DOMAIN=<SET-IN-.env>        # optional: appended to VKS_USERNAME if it has no '@' (e.g. WLD.SSO)
# VKS_CONTEXT_NAME=<SET-IN-.env>      # the vcf-CLI context NAME to type at the create prompt (e.g. sup66)
#                                     #   — DISTINCT from VKS_CONTEXT (kubeconfig context) above
# Commented so the code default (false) applies and a `make vks-login VKS_INSECURE_SKIP_TLS_VERIFY=1`
# / `.env` override is not clobbered. Set true to skip verifying the Supervisor's self-signed cert.
# VKS_INSECURE_SKIP_TLS_VERIFY=true
#
# --- kubectl-vsphere plugin login inputs (VKS_AUTH_METHOD=vsphere; pre-9 Supervisor) ---
# Reuses SUPERVISOR_HOST / VKS_NAMESPACE / VKS_USERNAME / VKS_INSECURE_SKIP_TLS_VERIFY above, plus:
# stage: set upfront (vCenter) — the VKS cluster name in vCenter (also feeds `vcf cluster kubeconfig get`)
# VKS_CLUSTER_NAME=<SET-IN-.env>      # the GUEST/workload Kubernetes cluster (a "VKS cluster") provisioned inside
#                                     #   VKS_NAMESPACE — DISTINCT from the Supervisor. This is where Gitea / Tekton /
#                                     #   javawebapp / Istio deploy; `vcf cluster kubeconfig get $VKS_CLUSTER_NAME` exports
#                                     #   ITS kubeconfig to $KUBECONFIG. (NB: the VKS-provided ArgoCD runs on the
#                                     #   SUPERVISOR, not here — see ARGOCD_NAMESPACE §4 for the deploy-target topology.)
# VKS_PASSWORD=<SET-IN-.env>          # vsphere method only — read via env by the plugin, never argv
#
# --- Lab CLIs (`make install-vcf-clis`) — Broadcom-LICENSED, operator-supplied ---
# The VCF/VKS lab CLIs (argocd-vcf + vcf Consumption CLI + its plugin bundle). NOT needed for
# the local KinD flow (that uses the upstream argocd from deps-prereqs).
# Supply them as a FOLDER: download the artifacts (however you have entitlement — the Broadcom
# support portal, an internal mirror) on an internet box, drop them ALL in one directory, and
# set VCF_CLI_SRC_DIR to it. The folder may hold per-arch files and/or the portal's multi-arch
# "…-Binaries-…" bundles; the installer picks the right one for the jump box's OS/arch.
# The pinned versions below select the matching archive; keep them in sync with your artifacts.
ARGOCD_VCF_VERSION=v3.0.19-vcf
VCF_CLI_VERSION=9.1.0.0.25296329
VCF_PLUGINS_VERSION=9.1.0.0300.25509668
# acquire: YOU provide it — download the licensed VCF/VKS CLI artifacts from the Broadcom portal with
#          your own entitlement and point this at the folder. They are NEVER fetched by this repo
#          (licensed binaries must not be re-hosted). Real-lab jump box only.
# VCF_CLI_SRC_DIR=<dir with the downloaded artifacts>   # REQUIRED for `make install-vcf-clis`
# BIN_DIR=~/.local/bin                                  # sudo-free install dir (default)

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# 7. Air-gap bundle (sneakernet)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
BUNDLE_DIR=./bundle
# Local dir crane pulls OCI layouts into before bundling / pushing.
IMAGE_CACHE_DIR=./bundle/images
# Mirror only ONE CPU architecture by default (matches the VKS/kind nodes) — keeps the
# cache ~5x smaller and mirroring much faster. Digest-pinned images (Tekton) are always
# mirrored multi-arch to preserve their list digest.
# All of the following are per-run toggles — commented so the CODE defaults apply and a
# `make … VAR=…` / env override is NOT clobbered when scripts source this file (load_env
# re-sources .env.example, so an UNcommented value here would overwrite `make mirror VAR=…`).
# MIRROR_ARCH=amd64         # single CPU arch to mirror (code default: amd64)
# MIRROR_ALL_ARCH=0         # 1 = mirror ALL architectures (larger, slower)
# MIRROR_RETRIES=5          # per-image crane retries (transient upstream/CDN resets)
# MIRROR_FORCE_PULL=0       # 1 = ignore the cache-skip sentinels, re-pull everything
# MIRROR_NO_PRUNE=0         # 1 = keep orphaned old-digest cache dirs (skip auto-prune)
# Bare-OS matrix for `make bootstrap-test` (each runs a full `make deps`, ~8-12 min/OS):
# BOOTSTRAP_TEST_OSES="ubuntu:22.04 ubuntu:24.04 ubuntu:26.04 photon:5.0"

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# 8. Tunable timings (readiness polling, HTTP checks) — seconds unless noted
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
READY_TIMEOUT_SECONDS=300
POLL_INTERVAL_SECONDS=5
CURL_MAX_TIME_SECONDS=10
# make verify (99-verify.sh) — EventListener readiness + PipelineRun-trigger waits. The
# Tekton Triggers clusterInterceptor CaBundle populates AFTER the EL starts, so the EL pod
# crash-loops briefly on a fresh cluster; verify waits for it to be Ready before pushing
# (else the one-shot Gitea webhook is lost -> no PipelineRun) and re-fires once per window.
EL_READY_TIMEOUT_SECONDS=180
PIPELINERUN_WAIT_SECONDS=120
# Resilient HTTP GET (http_get_retry) — used for transient-prone internet
# fetches like the ArgoCD install manifest from raw.githubusercontent.com,
# which rate-limits (HTTP 429). Retries with exponential backoff.
HTTP_GET_RETRIES=5
HTTP_GET_RETRY_DELAY_SECONDS=5
HTTP_CONNECT_TIMEOUT_SECONDS=10
HTTP_GET_MAX_TIME_SECONDS=60

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# 9. Pinned component versions (mirror of images/images.txt + .mise.toml)
#    Keep these aligned with images/images.txt; Renovate tracks the image tags.
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# renovate: datasource=github-releases depName=tektoncd/pipeline
TEKTON_PIPELINES_VERSION=v1.14.0
# renovate: datasource=github-releases depName=tektoncd/triggers
TEKTON_TRIGGERS_VERSION=v0.36.0
# Tekton Dashboard — the web UI for PipelineRuns/TaskRuns/logs, at TEKTON_DASHBOARD_HOST.
# Installed READ-ONLY (release.yaml; no mutation from the UI). The Dashboard has NO built-in
# auth — access is network/ingress-gated, so it needs no login (see .trivyignore rationale
# and the README "Access the UIs" note). Its image is mirrored from ghcr.io like the other
# Tekton controllers (derived from the release manifest, not images.txt).
# renovate: datasource=github-releases depName=tektoncd/dashboard
TEKTON_DASHBOARD_VERSION=v0.70.0
# The app RUNTIME image (eclipse-temurin JRE). Renovate-tracked in lockstep with
# images/images.txt; check-image-alignment fails CI if it drifts, and
# check-java-alignment fails if its major diverges from apps/java/javawebapp/pom.xml's java.version.
# (Only the JRE is mirrored — the in-cluster BUILD uses the maven:...-temurin image,
# so no standalone temurin JDK is needed.)
# renovate: datasource=docker depName=eclipse-temurin
TEMURIN_JRE_TAG=25.0.3_9-jre-jammy

# --- Go app (gowebapp) base images -------------------------------------------------------------
# Keep BOTH aligned with images/images.txt — `make check-image-alignment` reads each app's
# Dockerfile ARGs straight from apps/registry.tsv and fails on drift (a mirrored-but-unreferenced
# tag means Kaniko asks Harbor for an image it never received: MANIFEST_UNKNOWN at pipeline time).
GOLANG_BUILD_TAG=1.26.5-bookworm
# distroless publishes NO semver tags and `nonroot` MOVES, so it is pinned by DIGEST — the tag
# alone is not reproducible in an air-gap bundle.
DISTROLESS_STATIC_TAG=nonroot@sha256:b7bb25d9f7c31d2bdd1982feb4dafcaf137703c7075dbe2febb41c24212b946f

# CLI tools not covered by mise (downloaded by scripts/00-install-prereqs.sh).
# renovate: datasource=github-releases depName=tektoncd/cli extractVersion=^v(?<version>.*)$
TKN_VERSION=0.45.0
# The argocd CLI SHOULD match the ArgoCD server (ARGOCD_VERSION) major line — same
# argoproj/argo-cd product. Keep this aligned with ARGOCD_VERSION below; Renovate
# tracks both (same depName) and bumps them together.
# renovate: datasource=github-releases depName=argoproj/argo-cd
ARGOCD_CLI_VERSION=v3.4.5
# kubectl fallback version (only used by 00-install-prereqs.sh if mise didn't
# provide it). Kept aligned with .mise.toml's kubectl pin by check-toolchain-alignment.
# renovate: datasource=github-releases depName=kubernetes/kubernetes
KUBECTL_VERSION=v1.36.2

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# 10. KinD local end-to-end (simulates the "VKS-provided" Harbor + ArgoCD locally)
#     Used only by `make e2e-kind` / kind-* targets. On real VKS these are given.
#     The kind flow writes discovered values (HARBOR_URL, KUBECONFIG, ...) to a
#     gitignored .env.kind overlay that overrides the values above.
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
KIND_CLUSTER_NAME=vks-airgap-cicd
# Empty = use the kind binary's built-in (version-locked) default node image.
KIND_NODE_IMAGE=
# renovate: datasource=github-releases depName=kubernetes-sigs/cloud-provider-kind
CLOUD_PROVIDER_KIND_VERSION=v0.11.1
# renovate: datasource=helm depName=harbor registryUrl=https://helm.goharbor.io
HARBOR_CHART_VERSION=1.19.1
HARBOR_NAMESPACE=harbor
# renovate: datasource=github-releases depName=argoproj/argo-cd
ARGOCD_VERSION=v3.4.5
# ArgoCD 'admin' UI password for the LOCAL KinD ArgoCD. KinD ONLY — on real VKS,
# ArgoCD is provided by the lab with a lab-set password, so leave this blank there.
# Optional: set it (in .env, like GITEA_ADMIN_PASSWORD / HARBOR_PASSWORD) for a known,
# stable login; the KinD install applies it. Leave blank/commented to keep ArgoCD's
# auto-generated password — either way `make argocd-password` / `make creds` reveal it
# (they self-resolve the kubeconfig, so no kube-context juggling). Commented so it stays
# unset by default and the generated-password fallback works.
# stage: you choose (login for the component we install / KinD only)
# ARGOCD_ADMIN_PASSWORD=<SET-IN-.env>
